 and danger-through such unique practices as murmurations, specific alarm calls, distraction displays, and antipredator nest design. We also read about how birds adapt certain habits-preening, migration, breeding, and huddling-based on climate and climate change.Investigating avian tactics both familiar and unusual, Understanding Bird Behavior offers a fascinating, close-up look at the many ways birds conduct themselves in the wild. A comprehensive overview of bird behavior150 detailed color illustrations and photographsAn in-depth look at food gathering, courtship and mating, family organization, danger avoidance tactics, and climate-driven behaviorA list for further reading is provided  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aBirdsxBehavior. 7aNATURE / Animals / Birds.2bisacsh  aCalifornian junco.  aChatham Island robins.  aEgyptian vultures.  aNew Caledonian crows.  aalternative mating strategies.  aanis.  aant birds.  abishops.  ablack coucals.  ablackcap migration.  abowerbird.  abrood divisions.  abuffalo weaver.  aburrow nests.  acaching.  acamouflaged eggs.  acarrion crows.  achick mimicry.  acircadian rhythms.  acircannual rhythms.  acolored leg bands.  acommunal larders.  acoot chicks.  acrested auklet.  acrossbills.  acrows.  acuckoos.  adeception.  adelayed dispersal.  aeavesdropping.  aeconomics of feeding.  aegg and chick recognition.  aextra-pair copulations.  afairywrens.  afemale blue tits.  aflamingo.  aforced copulation.  afork-tailed drongos.  agreat tits.  ahabitat specialization.  aheritable egg placement.  ahoatzins.  ahouse husbands.  ahummingbird battles.  ainbreeding avoidance.  ainfanticide.  akakapo.  aleks.  along tails.  along-tailed tits.  amale-male competition.  amating systems.  amental 